[1.7]">Great set of questions. Let me work through them in order.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>When a trade secret accidentally leaks</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is actually one of the most interesting areas of trade secret =
law. If a secret leaks accidentally =E2=80=94 say an employee posts interna=
l docs publicly by mistake =E2=80=94 the company can try to pursue legal re=
medies to suppress further spread, but here's the brutal reality: <strong>o=
nce it's genuinely public, it's no longer a trade secret</strong>. Trade se=
cret protection depends entirely on the information remaining secret. You c=
an't un-ring the bell. The law doesn't give you a grace period the way pate=
nt law does.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Whether the <em>code itself</em> is still copyright protected after=
 leaking =E2=80=94 yes, absolutely. Copyright and trade secret are independ=
ent. The leak destroys the trade secret but copyright survives untouched, w=
hich is why companies like Microsoft and Valve have sent copyright takedown=
s over leaked source code even after it spread widely online.</p>
<hr class=3D"border-border-200 border-t-0.5 my-3 mx-1.5">
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Federal Copyright Requirements in the US</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Under the Copyright Act of 1976 (Title 17 U.S.C.), the formal requi=
rements are surprisingly minimal:</p>
<ol class=3D"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:l=
ast-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex=
-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Originality</stron=
g> =E2=80=94 the work must be independently created by the author and posse=
ss at least a minimal spark of creativity. This is a <em>very</em> low bar.=
 Famously established in <em>Feist Publications v. Rural Telephone Service<=
/em> (1991), where the Supreme Court held that a phone book's alphabetical =
listing wasn't original enough.</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Fixation</strong> =
=E2=80=94 the work must be fixed in a tangible medium of expression from wh=
ich it can be perceived, reproduced, or communicated. For code this is triv=
ially satisfied the moment you save a file.</li>
</ol>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">That's genuinely it for protection to <em>exist</em>. Two things th=
at are notably <strong>not</strong> required under modern US law:</p>
<ul class=3D"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:l=
