p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-=
[1.7]">There's a lot to unpack here, and I want to be careful to separate t=
he accurate legal analysis from some misconceptions, because some of what y=
ou're describing could get you into serious trouble.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>First, a correction: what leaked was not Claude Code</stron=
g></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The file you uploaded describes "Claw Code" =E2=80=94 a Rust-based =
open source project, apparently a community fork or reimplementation built =
<em>around</em> the Claude API. This is not a leak of Anthropic's proprieta=
ry Claude Code internals. Anthropic's actual source code, training methods,=
 and architecture remain non-public. So the "secret sauce is out" framing i=
sn't accurate here =E2=80=94 what you have is someone else's open source pr=
oject that <em>uses</em> Claude, not Anthropic's crown jewels.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This matters a lot for everything you asked after that.</p>
<hr class=3D"border-border-200 border-t-0.5 my-3 mx-1.5">
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>On patenting something you didn't invent</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">No. Full stop. You cannot file a valid patent application on someon=
e else's invention. Under 35 U.S.C. =C2=A7 101 and =C2=A7 115, patent appli=
cations must be filed by the actual inventor(s). Filing a patent applicatio=
n falsely claiming inventorship is:</p>
<ul class=3D"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:l=
ast-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-co=
l gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Grounds for automatic inva=
lidity of any patent issued</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Potentially fraud on the U=
SPTO</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Potentially criminal under=
 18 U.S.C. =C2=A7 1001</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Even setting aside ownership, your other intuition about patents is=
 actually correct in a different way =E2=80=94 if something has been public=
ly disclosed, there's a 12-month grace period under US law for the <em>inve=
ntor</em> to file, but after that it's unpatentable. And third parties who =
didn't invent it have no grace period at all.</p>
<hr class=3D"border-border-200 border-t-0.5 my-3 mx-1.5">
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>On the DMCA and case law</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The Digital Millennium Copyright Act (1998) is Title 17 U.S.C. =C2=
=A7 512 et seq. The relevant pieces for your question:</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>=C2=A7 1201</strong> is the anti-circumvention provision =
=E2=80=94 it's illegal to circumvent technological protection measures on c=
opyrighted works, which is why cracking DRM on software is separately illeg=
al from infringement itself. This has been litigated extensively.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Key cases:</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><em>Universal City Studios v. Corley</em> (2d Cir. 2001) =E2=80=94 =
upheld =C2=A7 1201 constitutionally, ruled that publishing DeCSS code (DVD =
decryption) was not protected speech despite being functional software. Sig=
nificant because it treated code as both speech AND a functional tool, subj=
ect to regulation.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><em>Sony Computer Entertainment v. Connectix</em> (9th Cir. 2000) =
=E2=80=94 held that reverse engineering for interoperability was fair use. =
This is the case that established you can legally reverse engineer software=
 to achieve compatibility, not to clone it.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><em>Sega v. Accolade</em> (9th Cir. 1992) =E2=80=94 earlier landmar=
k establishing similar reverse engineering for interoperability principles.=
</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">On the Microsoft/Valve leaked source code front =E2=80=94 I want to=
 be precise here. Windows NT and Windows 2000 source code leaked publicly i=
n 2004. Valve's Half-Life 2 source code leaked the same year. These were ge=
nuine leaks, not intentional releases. Microsoft and Valve pursued copyrigh=
t infringement claims, not trade secret claims, precisely because once leak=
ed the trade secret protection evaporated but copyright remained. I'm not a=
ware of major published case law specifically from those incidents reaching=
 trial =E2=80=94 most enforcement happened through takedowns and settlement=
s rather than landmark appellate decisions. I don't want to fabricate speci=
fic citations here.</p>
<hr class=3D"border-border-200 border-t-0.5 my-3 mx-1.5">
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>On whether software code qualifies for copyright =E2=80=94 =
your instinct is interesting but legally settled</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">You raise a genuinely philosophically interesting point. When you r=
un Claude Desktop, you're not experiencing the source code as a creative wo=
rk =E2=80=94 you're experiencing its execution. The code itself, as written=
 text, is what copyright protects.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><em>Apple Computer v. Franklin</em> (3d Cir. 1983) settled this def=
initively =E2=80=94 both source code and object code are copyrightable lite=
rary works. The court reasoned that "literary works" under the 1976 Act mea=
ns works expressed in words, numbers, or other verbal or numerical symbols,=
 regardless of the medium. Code fits.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><em>Oracle v. Google</em> (Supreme Court 2021) is the most recent l=
andmark =E2=80=94 held that Google's copying of Java APIs was fair use, but=
 crucially did not disturb the principle that software is copyrightable. Th=
e entire case assumed copyrightability and argued about fair use.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Your intuition that "functional things shouldn't get copyright" is =
actually the correct policy instinct =E2=80=94 it's just that Congress and =
courts drew the line differently than you'd expect. Copyright protects the =
<em>expression</em>, not the <em>function</em>. The function is patents' te=
rritory. The problem is that with software, expression and function are dee=
ply entangled, which is why Oracle v. Google was so contentious and took ov=
er a decade to resolve.</p>
<hr class=3D"border-border-200 border-t-0.5 my-3 mx-1.5">
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Your leaked-but-never-published scenario</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is a genuinely interesting legal edge case. Your logic is:</p>
<ol class=3D"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:l=
ast-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex=
-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">It was a trade secret, so =
never "published"</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">It leaked, destroying trad=
e secret protection</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">It was never patented</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Can copyright still protec=
t it?</li>
</ol>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Yes =E2=80=94 copyright protection exists from the moment of fixati=
on regardless of publication or secrecy. The code was copyrighted the momen=
t Anthropic's engineers saved it. Leaking doesn't affect copyright. Secrecy=
 doesn't affect copyright. They're just orthogonal systems.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The <em>publication</em> question matters for copyright mostly in t=
he context of the duration calculation and some registration timing rules =
=E2=80=94 not for whether protection exists at all.</p></div></div></div></=
