<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Ideas</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Concepts</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Themes</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Plot structures</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Story archetypes</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Genre conventions</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Style</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is codified in 17 U.S.C. =C2=A7 102(b) which literally states =
that copyright protection never extends to any idea, procedure, process, sy=
stem, method of operation, concept, principle, or discovery.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">So every hero's journey story ever written doesn't infringe Homer. =
Every star-crossed lovers story doesn't infringe Shakespeare. Every hardboi=
led detective story doesn't infringe Chandler. The <em>structure</em> and <=
em>ideas</em> are free for everyone. Only the specific expression is protec=
ted.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>On how many copyright infringers there have been throughout=
 human history</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Essentially zero, for most of human history, for a simple reason =
=E2=80=94 copyright is a remarkably recent invention.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The Statute of Anne in Britain in 1710 is generally considered the =
first modern copyright law. So for the roughly 300,000 years of homo sapien=
s existence, plus all of recorded civilization before 1710, there was no co=
pyright at all. Cave painters, Greek playwrights, medieval manuscript copyi=
sts, Renaissance painters, Shakespeare himself =E2=80=94 none of them opera=
ted under anything resembling modern copyright. Shakespeare famously borrow=
ed plots wholesale from Holinshed's Chronicles, Plutarch, Italian novellas.=
 Completely fine, legally and culturally.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Even after 1710 the regime was narrow, short in duration, and appli=
ed only to specific categories of work. The expansive copyright we have tod=
ay =E2=80=94 life plus 70 years, automatic upon fixation, covering essentia=
lly all creative expression =E2=80=94 is really a 20th century phenomenon, =
turbocharged by the 1976 Act and the Sonny Bono Copyright Term Extension Ac=
t of 1998.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The deeper point you're circling</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">You've essentially rediscovered what many legal scholars, economist=
s, and artists argue =E2=80=94 that modern copyright has expanded so far be=
yond its original purpose that it now <em>impedes</em> the creative traditi=
on it was meant to protect. The original constitutional basis in Article I =
Section 8 was "to promote the Progress of Science and useful Arts" =E2=80=
=94 a utilitarian justification, not a natural rights one. Limited monopoly=
 as an incentive, then works flowing into the public domain to enrich the c=
ommons.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The entire history of human creativity is one of influence, borrowi=
ng, transformation, and building on what came before. That's not a bug in c=
reativity, it's the engine of it. Copyright law at its best tries to protec=
t that engine by rewarding creators without locking up the raw materials ev=
eryone needs to create. Whether modern copyright actually achieves that bal=
ance is genuinely contested.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Lawrence Lessig, if you want to go deep on this, wrote <em>Free Cul=
ture</em> which covers exactly this tension and is actually available free =
online =E2=80=94 fittingly enough.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div cl=
