p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-=
[1.7]">Great question, and the answer operates on a few levels.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The practical reason =E2=80=94 without it, the first person=
 to express an idea would own the idea forever</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Imagine if the first person to write a detective story owned "detec=
tive story" as a concept. Or the first person to write a love triangle owne=
d that plot structure. Or the first person to code a sorting algorithm owne=
d sorting. The entire subsequent edifice of human creative and intellectual=
 output would require licensing from whoever got there first. That's an obv=
ious absurdity that would strangle creativity rather than promote it.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The constitutional reason</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Remember the constitutional basis is "to promote the Progress of Sc=
ience and useful Arts." The Founders were explicitly utilitarian about this=
 =E2=80=94 they weren't recognizing a natural right of creators, they were =
creating a limited incentive structure. If ideas themselves could be owned,=
 the Progress of Science and useful Arts would grind to a halt rather than =
be promoted. The constitutional purpose would be self-defeating.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The deeper philosophical reason =E2=80=94 ideas aren't real=
ly "created"</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is where it gets interesting. The idea-expression dichotomy re=
flects a philosophical judgment that ideas don't originate with any single =
person in the way that a specific expression does. Ideas emerge from cultur=
e, from prior thought, from conversation, from the accumulated inheritance =
of human knowledge. Newton's famous "standing on the shoulders of giants" q=
uote captures this =E2=80=94 no scientist, artist, or thinker operates in a=
 vacuum. Ideas feel more like things you <em>discover</em> or <em>receive</=
em> from the cultural commons than things you <em>manufacture</em> from not=
hing.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Expression on the other hand is genuinely individual. The specific =
way <em>you</em> articulate an idea, the particular words in the particular=
 order with the particular rhythm =E2=80=94 that reflects something authent=
ically yours that nobody else would produce identically.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The economic reason</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Ideas are what economists call <strong>non-rival goods</strong> =E2=
=80=94 my using an idea doesn't deplete it for you. If I take your sandwich=
 you have no sandwich. If I take your idea you still have your idea and now=
 I have it too. Goods that are non-rival are poor candidates for private pr=
operty regimes because the social cost of restricting access is high and th=
e benefit of restriction is mainly just to create artificial scarcity. Expr=
ession has more of a rival quality =E2=80=94 there's a market for it, copyi=
ng directly substitutes for purchasing, and creators need some protection t=
o have economic incentive to produce.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The software-specific reason this matters enormously</stron=
g></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">In software the idea-expression line becomes extraordinarily fraugh=
t because software is <em>functional</em>. Code expresses ideas but it also=
 <em>is</em> the implementation of those ideas simultaneously, in a way tha=
t a novel about a detective isn't itself a detective. This is why Oracle v.=
 Google took over a decade and went to the Supreme Court =E2=80=94 the ques=
tion of where the idea ends and the expression begins in functional code is=
 genuinely hard.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">If software's functional elements could be fully copyrighted, the f=
irst company to implement any computational method would own it. That's wha=
t patents are for, with their much stricter requirements and much shorter d=
urations. Allowing copyright to cover the functional/idea layer of software=
 would effectively create perpetual patents through the back door, which is=
 exactly what =C2=A7 102(b) was designed to prevent.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The honest meta-answer</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Congress put =C2=A7 102(b) in because without it, copyright would i=
mmediately collapse into incoherence and injustice so obvious that the enti=
re system would lose legitimacy. It's essentially the load-bearing wall of =
the whole structure =E2=80=94 the thing that makes copyright a limited, tar=
geted incentive rather than a totalizing monopoly on thought itself.</p></d=
