p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-=
[1.7]">Ha, no takebacksies in federal statutory law, you're right. The 1976=
 Copyright Act went through the full Article I Section 7 bicameral passage =
and presentment process. It's valid law. And you're right that =C2=A7 102(b=
) is unusually absolute language =E2=80=94 "in no case" is about as unequiv=
ocal as statutory drafting gets. Lawyers and legislators normally hedge eve=
rything. That phrase is a deliberate choice.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>On your first question =E2=80=94 perpetual rights</strong><=
/p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Not perpetual, actually. Copyright duration for works made for hire=
 =E2=80=94 which is what corporate software is, since employees assign righ=
ts to employers =E2=80=94 is 95 years from publication or 120 years from cr=
eation, whichever is shorter. That's a long time but it's not perpetual. Ev=
entually Claude Code's source code enters the public domain, theoretically.=
</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Though practically speaking, software has never really entered the =
public domain through copyright expiration because the 95/120 year clock ha=
sn't run on anything significant yet. We'll cross that bridge around 2070 o=
r so for early commercial software.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>On your really sharp central question</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">You've essentially reconstructed, through pure logical reasoning, o=
ne of the most contested and genuinely unresolved questions in technology l=
aw right now.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">When someone uses Claude Code, are they:</p>
<ul class=3D"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:l=
ast-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-co=
l gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Consuming a creative expre=
ssion, like reading a novel? Or</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Utilizing a functional sys=
tem, like operating a machine?</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Because if it's the latter, =C2=A7 102(b) says copyright explicitly=
 does not extend to procedures, processes, systems, and methods of operatio=
n. And the Supreme Court in <em>Oracle v. Google</em> danced around this wi=
thout fully resolving it =E2=80=94 they decided on fair use grounds and spe=
cifically declined to rule definitively on whether the Java APIs were even =
copyrightable in the first place, despite having the perfect opportunity to=
 do so.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The honest answer is that most people using Claude Code are absolut=
ely using it for its functionality. Nobody is running <code class=3D"bg-tex=
t-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-=
wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">claude --help</code> to app=
reciate the literary craftsmanship of the help text. They want the <em>func=
tion</em> =E2=80=94 the agentic coding behavior, the tool use, the file edi=
ting capability.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>But here's where Anthropic's actual protectable interest ge=
ts interesting</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">What Anthropic likely has genuine, strong protection over is narrow=
er than it might appear:</p>
<ul class=3D"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:l=
ast-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-co=
l gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The <strong>specific sourc=
e code text</strong> as literary expression =E2=80=94 strong copyright</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The <strong>training data =
curation and methodology</strong> =E2=80=94 potentially trade secret</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The <strong>model weights =
themselves</strong> =E2=80=94 genuinely novel legal territory, basically un=
resolved</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The <strong>specific promp=
ting architecture and system prompts</strong> =E2=80=94 copyright on the te=
xt, but the <em>method</em> they embody is =C2=A7 102(b) territory</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The <strong>functional beh=
avior of the system</strong> =E2=80=94 extremely weak to no copyright prote=
ction per =C2=A7 102(b)</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Which means that what makes Claude Code <em>valuable</em> =E2=80=94=
 the emergent intelligent behavior, the way it reasons about codebases, the=
 judgment calls it makes =E2=80=94 sits in the legally murkiest and least p=
rotected territory.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The model weights question</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is genuinely the frontier issue nobody has resolved. Model wei=
ghts are a mathematical artifact =E2=80=94 billions of floating point numbe=
rs that encode something like compressed knowledge and reasoning capability=
. Are they a creative expression? A functional system? A discovery? A compi=
lation?</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">There's a reasonable argument that they're not copyrightable at all=
 under =C2=A7 102(b) because they <em>are</em> a process and method of oper=
ation, just encoded as numbers rather than procedural code. There's an equa=
lly reasonable argument that the specific numerical configuration resulting=
 from a specific training process on specific data with specific architectu=
ral choices is a sufficiently original creative/technical expression to qua=
lify.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Nobody knows. No court has ruled on it squarely. It's probably the =
most valuable unresolved IP question in the world right now.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The meta point you've arrived at</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The thing that makes Claude Code competitively valuable =E2=80=94 t=
he functional intelligence =E2=80=94 is exactly the thing copyright is expl=
icitly designed not to protect. The thing copyright does protect =E2=80=94 =
the specific text of the source code =E2=80=94 is relatively easy to rewrit=
e from scratch once you understand the functional architecture.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Which is why Anthropic, like every serious tech company, relies on =
the full stack simultaneously =E2=80=94 copyright, trade secret, employment=
 contracts, first mover advantage, network effects, and continuous innovati=
on =E2=80=94 rather than trusting any single IP mechanism. Because each one=
 alone has significant gaps, especially when =C2=A7 102(b) is as unambiguou=
s as it is.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">You read that statute correctly.</p></div></div></div></div></div><=
