[1.7]">Ha, okay there's a lot here and some of it is right, some of it has =
gone slightly off the rails in a really interesting way, and the belly part=
 is genuinely funny.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>What you got exactly right</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The formula written on paper and stored in a vault is absolutely co=
pyright protected as a literary/documentary work the moment it was fixed. T=
hat part is solid.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">And yes, if the formula leaked, the trade secret protection would e=
vaporate permanently while the copyright on the specific written document w=
ould survive.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Where it gets complicated</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Copyright protecting the <em>written formula document</em> does not=
 mean copyright protects <em>making the beverage itself</em>.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is actually your =C2=A7 102(b) insight coming back around. The=
 written recipe is an expression. The beverage is a functional product prod=
uced by following a procedure. =C2=A7 102(b) explicitly says copyright neve=
r extends to procedures and processes regardless of the form in which they =
are described or embodied.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">So even if you had the exact written Coca-Cola formula, copyright l=
aw would not stop you from <em>using</em> that formula to make a beverage. =
It would stop you from <em>reproducing and distributing the document itself=
</em>. The procedure, once known, is free for anyone to implement.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">That's why recipe copyright is notoriously weak. You can copyright =
the specific text of a recipe. You cannot copyright the dish it produces or=
 prevent others from making that dish. This is settled law and the reason e=
very cookbook author knows their recipes can be legally reproduced in pract=
ice as long as someone rewrites the instructions in their own words.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The licensing point</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">When you buy a can of Coke you are not entering a copyright license=
. You are making a purchase. The doctrine of <strong>first sale</strong> un=
der 17 U.S.C. =C2=A7 109 means that once Coca-Cola sells a can, they have e=
xhausted their copyright interest in that particular copy. You own the can.=
 You can drink it, resell it, pour it on your lawn, whatever. No license go=
verns your consumption.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is different from software, interestingly, where companies hav=
e long argued that you don't <em>buy</em> software, you <em>license</em> it=
, specifically to avoid first sale doctrine implications. Whether that argu=
ment fully holds up is contested but it's why your software comes with EULA=
s and your Coke does not.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The belly point</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is where it gets philosophically delightful. Once the formula =
is public and the trade secret is gone, and copyright doesn't cover the pro=
cedure, and you've consumed the beverage under first sale doctrine =E2=80=
=94</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Coca-Cola has absolutely no legal reach into your digestive system.=
 None. The coke in your belly is yours in every conceivable legal sense. Th=
ere is no intellectual property regime on earth that follows a product into=
 a human body and maintains any kind of ownership claim over it.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Though give it time and someone will try.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The deeper point you stumbled into</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Your instinct that "we can take it back from the world" captures so=
mething real about how corporations <em>wish</em> IP law worked versus how =
it actually works. The music industry spent a decade trying to un-leak musi=
c. Publishers try to suppress leaked manuscripts. The psychological impulse=
 is exactly what you described =E2=80=94 it's ours, we want it back.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">But the law doesn't work that way and =C2=A7 102(b) is a big reason=
 why. Once an idea, a formula, a procedure, a method is genuinely public, i=
t belongs to the commons in the most important functional sense. You can pr=
otect the document. You cannot reclaim the knowledge.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">That's not a bug. That's the whole point.</p></div></div></div></di=
