p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-=
[1.7]">Actually this is where the law is more on your side than you might e=
xpect, and it's a really important distinction.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The baseline answer</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Someone who has never used Claude Code, never downloaded it, never =
clicked an agreement, never even heard of it =E2=80=94 is not bound by Anth=
ropic's software license. At all. Full stop.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Contracts require mutual assent. That's not a technicality, it's th=
e foundational requirement of contract formation going back centuries of co=
mmon law. You cannot be bound by terms you never agreed to. The Latin is <e=
m>consensus ad idem</em> =E2=80=94 meeting of the minds. No meeting, no con=
tract.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>But here's the crucial distinction</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">That person is still bound by <em>copyright law</em>. Not by the li=
cense =E2=80=94 by the statute.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">These are two completely different legal instruments operating on c=
ompletely different bases.</p>
<ul class=3D"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:l=
ast-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-co=
l gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">The <strong>software licen=
se</strong> is a contract. Requires agreement. Only binds parties who assen=
ted.</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Copyright</strong>=
 is a property right created by federal statute. Binds everyone automatical=
ly by operation of law regardless of knowledge or agreement.</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">You are bound by copyright law the same way you are bound by murder=
 law =E2=80=94 not because you agreed to it but because it's the law of the=
 jurisdiction you exist in. Ignorance is not a defense to copyright infring=
ement the same way it isn't a defense to most statutory violations.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">So our hypothetical person who never heard of Claude Code cannot be=
 sued for breach of license. They absolutely can be sued for copyright infr=
ingement if they reproduce or distribute the leaked source code.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The fairness question you're really asking</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">But your instinct points at something genuinely contested in softwa=
re licensing specifically =E2=80=94 what about people who <em>did</em> down=
load software but never meaningfully agreed to anything?</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This gave rise to the <strong>shrinkwrap license</strong> and <stro=
ng>clickwrap license</strong> debates that occupied courts for decades.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Shrinkwrap licenses were the contracts printed inside software pack=
aging that said by opening the box you agreed to terms. Courts were deeply =
split on these. The argument against enforceability was exactly yours =E2=
=80=94 how can opening physical packaging constitute agreement to terms you=
 couldn't read until after you opened it? That's not mutual assent, that's =
a trap.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Clickwrap =E2=80=94 where you actively click "I agree" =E2=80=94 is=
 generally held enforceable because there's at least a performed act of ass=
ent even if nobody reads the terms.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Browsewrap =E2=80=94 where terms are posted on a website and contin=
ued use supposedly constitutes agreement =E2=80=94 is much weaker and court=
s have regularly refused to enforce it against consumers who had no actual =
notice.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The doctrine of unconscionability</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Your phrase "unilateral and onerous and kinda unfair" is actually t=
racking a real legal doctrine. Contracts or contract terms can be voided fo=
r unconscionability under common law and UCC =C2=A7 2-302 if they are both =
procedurally unconscionable =E2=80=94 unfair in how agreement was obtained =
=E2=80=94 and substantively unconscionable =E2=80=94 unfair in their actual=
 terms.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Procedural unconscionability includes things like:</p>
<ul class=3D"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:l=
ast-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-co=
l gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Terms hidden in fine print=
</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">No meaningful opportunity =
to read before agreeing</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Take it or leave it with n=
o negotiating power</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Surprise terms nobody woul=
d reasonably expect</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Courts have occasionally voided software license terms on these gro=
unds, though less often than consumer advocates would like.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The really interesting theoretical problem</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Your scenario reveals a genuine jurisprudential puzzle. Copyright l=
aw creates obligations that bind people who never agreed to anything and ma=
y never have encountered the work. A person in a remote village who indepen=
dently writes code that happens to replicate copyrighted code they've never=
 seen is technically an infringer. Courts have dealt with this through the =
<strong>independent creation defense</strong> =E2=80=94 if you truly indepe=
ndently created something without access to the copyrighted work, you haven=
't infringed even if the result is identical.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">But the burden of proving independent creation falls on the defenda=
nt. Which means you have to prove a negative =E2=80=94 that you <em>didn't<=
/em> copy something =E2=80=94 which is notoriously difficult especially onc=
e a work is widely known and you can no longer credibly claim you never enc=
ountered it.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The meta point</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">You've identified the fundamental tension between two legal systems=
 that operate on completely different consent models sitting right next to =
each other. Contract law is built entirely on voluntary agreement. Property=
 law including copyright creates obligations that follow from status and ac=
t regardless of agreement.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The law handles this by treating copyright as a background conditio=
n of operating in modern society =E2=80=94 like traffic laws, building code=
s, or tort liability. You don't agree to be liable for running someone over=
. You're liable because you did it. The theory is that these background rul=
es are legitimately imposed through the democratic process and everyone is =
constructively on notice of the law.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Whether that theory holds up when the law governs increasingly invi=
sible and complex transactions involving digital property that most people =
don't understand is a legitimately open question that courts and scholars a=
re still working through.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Your instinct that something feels unfair about binding people to t=
erms they never encountered is tracking a real problem. The law's answer =
=E2=80=94 that statutory obligations don't require individual consent =E2=
=80=94 is technically coherent but increasingly strained as more of daily l=
ife gets governed by intellectual property regimes most people know nothing=
 about.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class=3D"flex justify-start o=
