d more interesting.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Software patents absolutely exist and are granted constantl=
y</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The USPTO issues thousands of software patents every year. Major te=
ch companies hold enormous software patent portfolios. IBM, Microsoft, Goog=
le, Apple, Qualcomm =E2=80=94 these companies hold tens of thousands of sof=
tware patents each and they are very real and very enforceable.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">So the blunt answer is: yes, software can be patented.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>But it's genuinely complicated and the law is unsettled</st=
rong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The Supreme Court has repeatedly tried to draw a line between paten=
table software inventions and unpatentable abstract ideas implemented in co=
de, without ever drawing that line cleanly.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The key cases in rough chronological order:</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><em>Gottschalk v. Benson</em> (1972) =E2=80=94 mathematical algorit=
hms themselves are not patentable. You can't patent math.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><em>Diamond v. Diehr</em> (1981) =E2=80=94 but a process that <em>u=
ses</em> a mathematical algorithm to solve a practical industrial problem c=
an be patented. The Court upheld a patent on a rubber curing process that h=
appened to use a mathematical formula.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><em>Bilski v. Kappos</em> (2010) =E2=80=94 attempted to patent a me=
thod of hedging commodity risk. Court said no, it was an abstract idea. But=
 declined to say software patents were categorically invalid.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><em>Alice Corp. v. CLS Bank</em> (2014) =E2=80=94 the most importan=
t recent case. Established the <strong>Alice test</strong>, a two step inqu=
iry:</p>
<ol class=3D"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:l=
ast-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex=
-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Is the claim directed at a=
n abstract idea?</li>
<li class=3D"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">If yes, does it contain an=
 inventive concept that transforms it into something significantly more tha=
n the abstract idea itself?</li>
</ol>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">If you fail both steps your software patent is invalid. The problem=
 is nobody can reliably predict how courts will apply this test. It's notor=
iously inconsistent. The same claim might survive at one court and fail at =
another.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>What this means practically</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">After Alice, patent examiners and courts invalidated enormous numbe=
rs of previously granted software patents. Particularly business method pat=
ents =E2=80=94 things like "do X but on the internet" or "do X but on a sma=
rtphone" that had been granted freely in the 1990s and 2000s suddenly becam=
e vulnerable.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">But genuinely technical software innovations =E2=80=94 novel compre=
ssion algorithms, specific implementations of cryptographic methods, partic=
ular approaches to rendering graphics, concrete solutions to specific compu=
tational problems =E2=80=94 these remain patentable if they meet the standa=
rd requirements of novelty, utility, and non-obviousness plus survive Alice=
 scrutiny.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The core tension</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Here's why it stays messy. Every software patent describes somethin=
g that is at some level of abstraction an abstract idea. Addition is an abs=
tract idea. Sorting is an abstract idea. Encrypting data is an abstract ide=
a. The question is always whether the specific claimed implementation is su=
fficiently concrete and inventive to deserve protection or whether it's jus=
t dressing up an abstract idea in technical clothing.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">That line is genuinely hard to draw and the Court has essentially a=
dmitted it can't draw it precisely. Which leaves everyone =E2=80=94 invento=
rs, patent examiners, investors, competitors, lawyers =E2=80=94 operating u=
nder significant uncertainty.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Looping back to Anthropic</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Anthropic has filed patents. Machine learning companies generally d=
o. The specific training methodologies, architectural innovations, particul=
ar solutions to concrete technical problems =E2=80=94 these can potentially=
 be patented if they meet the requirements.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">But the most valuable things =E2=80=94 the emergent behavior of a t=
rained model, the general approach of constitutional AI, the broad concept =
of RLHF =E2=80=94 these sit much closer to the abstract idea end of the spe=
ctrum and would face serious Alice challenges.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Which brings you right back to why trade secret protection remains =
so important for AI companies despite its fragility. The patent system's un=
certainty around software and the =C2=A7 102(b) problem with copyright mean=
s that for the crown jewels of AI development, secrecy is often the most re=
liable protection available =E2=80=94 which is exactly the Coca-Cola logic =
all over again.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class=3D"flex justify=
