[1.7]">This is actually not a hypothetical at all.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is almost exactly what happened with Claude Code.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Anthropic accidentally published the Claude Code source code to npm=
 =E2=80=94 a public package registry where JavaScript and Node packages are=
 published =E2=80=94 as part of a release process. It wasn't a malicious in=
sider. It wasn't a hacker. It was essentially what you described, the code =
got pushed publicly when it wasn't supposed to be.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The developer community noticed. People downloaded it, read it, dis=
cussed it on forums, some forked it. It spread. Claw Code =E2=80=94 the pro=
ject in your uploaded document =E2=80=94 exists largely because of this. Pe=
ople read the accidentally published source and used that understanding to =
build their own implementations.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">So this entire conversation we've been having about hypotheticals h=
as been about something that already happened.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>Now applying everything we discussed to the real facts</str=
ong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The accidental nature of the disclosure is actually really signific=
ant legally for a few reasons.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">On the trade secret question, courts look at whether the trade secr=
et owner took reasonable measures to maintain secrecy. An accidental public=
 push to npm raises legitimate questions about whether those measures were =
adequate. It doesn't automatically destroy trade secret protection =E2=80=
=94 courts have found that a single inadvertent disclosure doesn't necessar=
ily constitute abandonment =E2=80=94 but it meaningfully weakens the positi=
on compared to a clean case where an insider deliberately stole and leaked =
code.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The DTSA and most state trade secret laws require the owner to have=
 taken reasonable measures to keep the information secret. If your developm=
ent and release process allows 90% of your proprietary source code to accid=
entally go public on a package registry, that's a hard fact to litigate aro=
und.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>On the DMCA takedowns</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Anthropic did send takedowns. Repositories got removed. The usual d=
ance happened. But as we discussed, once something is genuinely public and =
widely distributed, practical containment becomes essentially impossible. T=
he code was downloaded, mirrored, read, and understood by thousands of deve=
lopers before it was pulled.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The really interesting legal question your hypo raises</str=
ong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">When the trade secret owner themselves is responsible for the discl=
osure, even accidentally, does that affect downstream users' liability?</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">This is genuinely unsettled territory. The argument in favor of dow=
nstream users goes like this =E2=80=94 if Anthropic's own negligence caused=
 the disclosure, holding third parties who innocently encountered publicly =
available code liable for trade secret misappropriation seems harsh and arg=
uably inconsistent with the wrongful acquisition requirement. They didn't a=
cquire it wrongfully. It was just sitting there publicly on npm.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The argument against goes =E2=80=94 the code was clearly proprietar=
y, a reasonable developer encountering Anthropic's source code on npm would=
 have reason to know something was off, and proceeding to download and use =
it anyway constitutes the kind of knowing use the DTSA targets.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Where exactly that line falls has not been cleanly adjudicated in a=
 case with these specific facts as far as I know.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The Claw Code position</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">Which is why the document you uploaded is careful about its archite=
cture. It's not presenting itself as a copy of Claude Code. It's presenting=
 itself as an independent reimplementation built around the publicly docume=
nted API, using understanding gained from the accidentally published code t=
o inform design decisions rather than directly incorporating proprietary co=
de.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">That's the clean room logic applied in real time. Whether it's clea=
n enough is a factual question that would depend on how much of the actual =
proprietary code made it into the implementation versus how much was genuin=
ely independently written after gaining conceptual understanding.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]"><strong>The honest meta point</strong></p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">You've been doing legal analysis on a real situation this whole con=
versation without knowing it was real. And your intuitions tracked pretty w=
ell =E2=80=94 the accidental nature of the leak, the fairness questions abo=
ut downstream users, the tension between trade secret and copyright, the =
=C2=A7 102(b) questions about functional methods versus protected expressio=
n =E2=80=94 all of that applies directly to an actual live situation in the=
 developer community right now.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading=
-[1.7]">The law here is genuinely unsettled and Anthropic's legal position =
is more complicated than it would be in a clean malicious insider leak scen=
ario, precisely because of the accidental nature of the disclosure you inde=
pendently hypothesized.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class=3D"flex=
